'''Herne Hill railway station''' is a passenger [[railway station]] in [[Herne Hill]] in the [[London Borough of Lambeth]], [[South London]], England, on the boundary between [[London fare zones]] 2 and 3. Direct [[Rail transport|rail services]] are provided by [[First Capital Connect]] to [[Blackfriars station|London Blackfriars]], [[Farringdon station|Farringdon]], [[St Pancras railway station|St. Pancras International]] and [[Luton Airport Parkway railway station|Luton Airport]] on the [[Thameslink]] route and by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]] to [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]] and [[Orpington railway station|Orpington]] on the [[Chatham Main Line]]. Trains to Victoria call at [[Brixton railway station|Brixton]], where passengers can transfer to the [[London Underground]].

The station building on [[Railton Road]] was opened in 1862 by the [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]]. Initially passengers could travel only to Victoria, but by 1869 direct services were available to the [[City of London]], [[King's Cross Thameslink railway station|King's Cross]], [[Kingston railway station (London)|Kingston]] (via [[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]]) and [[Kent]], including express trains to [[List of railway stations in Dover#Former stations|Dover Harbour]] for [[boat train|boat trains]] to continental Europe. The arrival of the railways transformed Herne Hill from a wealthy suburb with large residential estates into a densely populated urban area.

The future pattern of passenger services is uncertain. [[Network Rail]] has recommended terminating all northbound First Capital Connect services from Herne Hill at Blackfriars from 2018; passengers for other central London stations on the Thameslink route would then have to change trains at Blackfriars.

==Description==
Herne Hill railway station sits at the bottom of the hill that gives the area its name and is close to [[Brockwell Park]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Herne Hill Society |title= A Short History of Herne Hill |year=2011 |publisher= Herne Hill Society |isbn=978-1-873520-83-3 |page=13 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref> The section of Railton Road outside the station is [[Living street|mixed usage]] for pedestrians and vehicles.<ref>[http://www.lambeth.gov.uk/Services/TransportStreets/HerneHillJunctionImprovementScheme.htm Herne Hill junction improvement scheme] Lambeth Council. Retrieved 2 May 2012</ref>

The  [[Chatham Main Line]] and [[Sutton Loop]] railway lines through Herne Hill are elevated above road-level on a brick [[viaduct]] that runs north<U+2013>south. The station's 1862 [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic]], [[polychrome]] brick<ref name="Pevsner">{{cite book |last1=Cherry |first1=Bridget |last2=Pevsner |first2=Nikolaus |title=[[Pevsner Architectural Guides|Buildings of England]], London: South, Volume 2 |year=1983 |publisher=Penguin |location=London |page=363 |ref=harv }}</ref> building is on the western side of the viaduct, although passengers can also access the station from the east via a foot tunnel entrance on Milkwood Road.<ref name="nationalrail">[http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/stations/sjp/HNH/plan.html Herne Hill Station Plan] National Rail. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref> The building houses a ticket office and newsagent, and was [[Listed building|Grade II listed]] in 1998: the listing notes the station's arched doorways, Welsh slate roof and decorative brickwork.<ref>[http://list.english-heritage.org.uk/resultsingle.aspx?uid=1376144 List entry Number: 1376144, Herne Hill railway station, entrance block only] English Heritage. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref> It was described by [[Pevsner Architectural Guides|Cherry and Pevsner]] as a "handsome group"<ref name="Pevsner"/> and featured on the cover of a book about London's railway architecture.<ref>{{cite book |last=Symes |first=Rodney |title= Railway Architecture of Greater London |year=1973 |publisher= Osprey Publishing |location=Reading |isbn=978-0-85045-123-8 |at= Cover |ref=harv }}</ref> 

The four platforms are split between two [[island platform]]s;<ref name="nationalrail" /> northbound trains call at the western platform and southbound trains at the eastern platform,<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=G.R.S. |title= Railway Accidents: Report on the Collision which occurred on 6th November, 1947, at Herne Hill on the Southern Railway |year=1948 |publisher=Ministry of Transport |location=London |url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_HerneHill1947.pdf |at=Point of collision diagram |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>  providing passengers with [[cross-platform interchange]] between the two routes.

There are [[Level junction|flat junction]]s at each end of the station: Herne Hill North Junction, where the lines to [[Loughborough Junction railway station|Loughborough Junction]] and [[Brixton railway station|Brixton]] stations diverge; and Herne Hill South Junction, where the lines to [[West Dulwich railway station|West Dulwich]] and [[Tulse Hill railway station|Tulse Hill]] stations diverge.<ref>{{cite book |last=Brown |first=Joe |title= London Railway atlas |year=2009 |publisher= Ian Allan |location=Hersham |isbn=978-0-71103-397-9 |page=32 |ref=harv }}</ref> First Capital Connect and Southeastern services must cross each other's paths at the junctions, constraining capacity on both routes.<ref>[[#NetworkRail_March2008|Network Rail March 2008]], p. 54.</ref> The station also has a [[Siding (rail)|turnback siding]] (requiring the driver to change from one end of the train to the other) on its eastern side, adjacent to Milkwood Road.<ref name="southernelectric">[http://www.southernelectric.org.uk/tocnews/tlko0blackfriars01.html Thameslink Key Output Zero <U+2013> Blackfriars Terminus Platforms Closure] Southern Electric Group. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref>

==History==
The area now known as Herne Hill had been a rural part of the Manor of Milkwell since the 13th century.<ref>[[#Survey_1956|Survey of London 1956]], pp. 141<U+2013>145.</ref> Two [[Tributary|tributaries]] of the [[River Effra]] met at the undeveloped site of the future station;<ref name="LostRivers">{{cite book |last=Talling |first=Paul |title=London's Lost Rivers |year=2011 |publisher=Random House |isbn=1-84794-597-X |page=54 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref> it was known as Island Green until the 18th century.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=James |title=The story of Norwood |year=1973 |publisher=London Borough of Lambeth |isbn=0-9501893-3-2 |page=10 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref> 

In 1783, a timber merchant, Samuel Sanders, bought Herne Hill from the Manor.<ref>[[#Survey_1956|Survey of London 1956]], pp. 1<U+2013>17.</ref> Sanders granted leases for large plots of land to wealthy families &ndash; [[John Ruskin]] spent his childhood at an estate on Herne Hill. The Effra was covered over in the 1820s;<ref name="LostRivers" /> and the area had become an upper-class suburb by the mid-19th century (a contemporary author referred to the hill as "the Elysium" for merchants).<ref>{{cite book |last=Hone |first=William |title=The Every-day Book and Table Book (Volume 2) |year=1830 |publisher=T. Tegg |page=557 |ref=harv }}</ref> The opening of the railway station, which provided convenient and cheap access to central London, started the urbanisation of Herne Hill.<ref name="Surveyof">[[#Survey_1956|Survey of London 1956]], pp. 146<U+2013>154.</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Long|first=Helen C.|title=The Edwardian House: The Middle-Class Home in Britain, 1880<U+2013>1914|year=1993|publisher=Manchester University Press|isbn=0-7190-3728-X|page=55}}</ref> All of the large estates were eventually cleared to make way for many smaller houses.<ref>{{cite book |last=Herne Hill Society |title= A Glance at the History of Herne Hill |year=1992 |publisher= Herne Hill Society  |page=7 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref> An 1870 railway travel guide noted the population of Herne Hill was 701;<ref>{{cite book |title= The ABC; or, Alphabetical railway guide: showing at a glance how and when to go from London to the different stations in Great Britain, and return, etc. |year=1870 |publisher= W. Tweedie  |page=55 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref> the contemporaneous development of new residential streets would increase the population by 3,000.<ref>[http://www.hernehillsociety.org.uk/index.php/news_articles/view/19th_century The nineteenth century] Herne Hill Society. Retrieved 3 May 2012</ref>

===Construction===
In the late 1850s, the [[East Kent Railway]] had ambitions to run passenger trains between Kent and London, but it did not own any railway lines in inner London. It reached an agreement with the [[London, Brighton and South Coast Railway]] (LB&SCR) in 1858 to use its [[West End of London and Crystal Palace Railway|West End and Crystal Palace line]] to access [[Battersea]] and (from 1860) [[London Victoria station|Victoria]]. This arrangement incurred costly access fees, but it was necessary until the company obtained Parliamentary authority to build in London.<ref>[[#Kidner_1968|Kidner 1968]], p. 327.</ref><ref>{{cite book |last= Turner| first= John Howard | year=1978 | title= The London Brighton and South Coast Railway 2 Establishment and Growth | publisher= B.T Batsford | location = London |isbn=0-7134-1198-8 |page=121 }}</ref>

In August 1860, the Metropolitan Extensions Act granted the [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway]] (LCDR; the successor to the East Kent company) the right to build two inner London lines: one from [[Beckenham Junction station|Beckenham Junction]] to Victoria via Herne Hill; and another, a {{convert|4.5|mi|km|1|lk=in|abbr=on}} extension known as the [[London, Chatham and Dover Railway#Second London line|City Branch]], from Herne Hill to [[Farringdon station|Farringdon]].<ref>[[#White_1961|White 1961]], p. 36.</ref> Herne Hill station and the first line section to be completed, from Victoria to Herne Hill via [[Stewarts Lane]] and {{Stnlnk|Brixton}}, opened on 25 August 1862.<ref name="White">[[#White_1961|White 1961]], p. 33.</ref>
[[File:Herne Hill Station 1863.jpg|thumb|left|An illustration from ''The Building News''; note the stairway on the left for accessing the upper floor, and the wider canopy.|alt=Black and white line drawing of a two story gothic revival building having a square tower to its left and a railway viaduct to the right.]]
The station was designed by architect [[John Taylor (architect)|John Taylor]]<ref>{{cite book |last=Wheeler |first=Michael |title=The Lamp of Memory: Ruskin, Tradition and Architecture |year=1993 |publisher=Manchester University Press |location=Manchester |isbn= 0-7190-3710-7 |page=180 |ref=harv }}</ref> and railway engineers [[Joseph Cubitt]] and J.T. Turner.<ref name="Surveyof" /> The building was intended to impress: it had tea rooms offering buffets,<ref>{{cite book |last=Course |first=Edwin |title= London Railways |year=1962 |publisher= B.T Batsford | location = London |page=265 |ref=harv }}</ref> decorative brickwork and a tower (which also served the practical function of concealing the water tank for steam locomotives).<ref>[[#Herne_Hill_Society_2003|Herne Hill Society 2003]], p. 10.</ref> ''The Building News'' described the station in 1863 as "spacious and convenient&nbsp;... and of the very best quality". It also stated that "an unusual amount of decorative taste has been displayed" in the station's construction; even the viaduct was praised as "one of the most ornamental pieces of work we have ever seen attempted on a railway" for its fine brickwork.<ref>{{cite journal |title=London, Chatham and Dover Railway |journal=The Building News |volume=10 |date=9 January 1863 |page=27}}</ref> The station's design prompted the journal to write a 2,000-word editorial bemoaning the comparatively poor architectural quality of other contemporary civil engineering projects.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Herne Hill railway station |journal=The Building News |volume=10 |date=1 May 1863 |page=327}}</ref> An architectural critic later noted the station was "eulogised" by journals upon its opening and that its architecture was still seen as exemplary at the end of the 19th century.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Frampton |first1=George |year=1896 |title= |journal=The Studio |volume=7 |issue= |page=24 |publisher=National Magazine Co}}</ref>
 
There were initially two platforms at the station: [[Railroad_direction#United_Kingdom|up and down]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Stanford |first=Edward |title= Stanford's Library Map Of London And Its Suburbs 1864: East Brixton, South London Railway, London Chatham & Dover Railway, Herne Hill, & Dulwich |year=1864 |ref=harv }}</ref> Up was accessed from the upper floor of the station building via a stairway outside the building and down from an island platform. The station's original [[Signalling control|signal box]], elevated above the railway viaduct at the junction between Norwood Road and Half Moon Lane, was a prominent feature in Herne Hill for many years.<ref>[http://landmark.lambeth.gov.uk/display_page.asp?section=landmark&id=1027 Herne Hill Station]. Lambeth Council. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref>

The land for the station was compulsorily purchased from Thomas Vyse, manufacturer of straw hats and owner of the Abbey, an estate at 70 Herne Hill; the station and much of the viaduct were built on part of the Abbey's grounds.<ref>[[#Herne Hill Society 2003|Herne Hill Society 2003]], p. 78.</ref> A new road (appropriately, Station Road) was built from the station to the junction of Norwood Road and Half Moon Lane, Herne Hill's main thoroughfare.<ref name="HerneHill">[[#Herne Hill Society 2003|Herne Hill Society 2003]], p. 11.</ref>

On 6 October 1863, the City Branch opened from Herne Hill as far as {{Stnlnk|Elephant & Castle}}, via {{Stnlnk|Camberwell}} and {{Stnlnk|Walworth Road}} (the platforms at [[Loughborough Junction railway station|Loughborough Junction]], now the closest station to Herne Hill, opened in 1872).<ref name="White_a">[[#White_1961|White 1961]], p. 37.</ref> The line from Beckenham Junction reached Herne Hill from the south in July 1863,<ref name="White" /> connecting the station to the LCDR's lines in Kent, and finally allowing the LCDR to avoid using the LB&SCR's tracks to access Victoria from Kent.<ref>{{cite book |last= Nock |first= O.S. |year=1961 |title=The South Eastern and Chatham Railway |publisher=Ian Allan |location = London | pages = 53, 60 |oclc=254188896}}</ref> By June 1864, the City Branch had been extended to [[Blackfriars Bridge railway station]] (on the south bank of the [[River Thames]]) via {{Stnlnk|Borough Road}}.<ref name="White_a" /> [[Blackfriars Railway Bridge]] was then built across the Thames and a terminus for trains from the south opened at [[Ludgate Hill railway station|Ludgate Hill]] on 1 June 1865.<ref>{{cite journal |year=1988 |journal=The Railway magazine |volume=134 |page=364 |location=London}}</ref>
{{MetropolitanExtensions}}
[[Snow Hill tunnel]] opened on 1 January 1866, enabling trains from Herne Hill to reach Farringdon and completing the Metropolitan Extension. In 1868, the LB&SCR opened a suburban line from [[London Bridge station|London Bridge]] to [[Sutton railway station (London)|Sutton]] via {{Stnlnk|Tulse Hill}}. A {{convert|1|mi|km|1|lk=in|abbr=on}} extension from Tulse Hill to Herne Hill opened on 1 January 1869.<ref>{{cite book |last=Kidner |first=R.W. |title=The London, Chatham and Dover Railway |year=1952 |publisher=Oakwood Press |page=10 |location =South Godstone, Surrey |oclc= 12264028  |ref=harv }}</ref>

===Early services===
From July 1863, the LCDR's trains between Victoria and Kent ran through Herne Hill. Passengers could travel to destinations in continental Europe via a connecting steamboat from [[List of railway stations in Dover#Former stations|Dover Harbour]] to [[Calais]];<ref>{{cite book |last=Reynolds |first=Si<U+00E2>n |title= Paris-Edinburgh: Cultural Connections in the Belle Epoque |year=2007 |publisher= Ashgate Publishing  |page=14 |location= Farnham |ref=harv }}</ref> these [[boat train]] services left Victoria and Ludgate Hill simultaneously and were joined at Herne Hill.<ref>{{cite book|title=Ward and Lock's Pictorial Guide to London|year=1879|publisher=Ward, Lock and Co, Ltd|page=36}}</ref> Express journeys from Herne Hill to Dover, a distance of {{convert|74|mi|km|1|lk=in|abbr=on}}, took 1 hour, 36 minutes, at an average speed of {{convert|46.25|mph|kph|1|lk=in|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Willock |first=H.B |year=1884 |title=English Express Trains in 1871; and a Comparison Between Them and Those of 1883 |journal=Journal of the Statistical Society of London |volume=47 |issue=2 |page=294 |publisher=Royal Statistical Society |doi=10.2307/2979189}}</ref> Services to London were split at Herne Hill to give passengers easier access to the [[City of London]] and beyond;<ref>[[#White_1961|White 1961]], p. 39.</ref> the LCDR began operating direct services to [[King's Cross Thameslink railway station|King's Cross]] and Barnet (now [[High Barnet tube station]]) from Herne Hill when Snow Hill tunnel opened.<ref name="Jackson">[[#Jackson_1969|Jackson 1969]], p. 194.</ref>

A popular workmen's train (one [[<U+00A3>sd|penny]] per journey) ran between Ludgate Hill and Victoria via Herne Hill from 1865. Trains left from both termini at 04:55 and returned at 18:15.<ref>[[#White_1971|White 1971]], p. 36.</ref> The LCDR was compelled to operate this service by Parliament to compensate for the large number of working class homes destroyed in [[Camberwell]] during the construction of the City Branch.<ref>[[#Kidner_1968|Kidner 1968]], p. 333.</ref> Regular one-way fares to Ludgate Hill were eight pence, six pence and four pence for first, second and third class respectively (or return for one [[<U+00A3>sd|shilling]], nine pence and seven pence respectively), with journey times of 15 minutes on express services and 26 minutes when calling at all stops.<ref>{{cite book |title= The ABC; or, Alphabetical railway guide: showing at a glance how and when to go from London to the different stations in Great Britain, and return, etc. |year=1870 |publisher= W. Tweedie  |pages=10,55 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref>

Both the [[Great Northern Railway (Great Britain)|Great Northern Railway]] (GNR) and the [[London and South Western Railway]] (LSWR) helped fund the Metropolitan Extensions (<U+00A3>320,000 and <U+00A3>310,000 respectively; <U+00A3>{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|320000|1860|{{CURRENTYEAR}}|r=0}}}} and <U+00A3>{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|310000|1860|{{CURRENTYEAR}}|r=0}}}} as of {{CURRENTYEAR}}{{Inflation-fn|UK}}) in return for the right to use the LCDR's tracks.<ref name="Jackson_a">[[#Jackson_1969|Jackson 1969]], p. 193.</ref> The GNR ran trains between [[Hatfield railway station|Hatfield]] and Herne Hill from August 1866 until March 1868 (when the trains were diverted to Victoria via Loughborough Junction);<ref name="Jackson" /> this was a busy all-stops service, with 15 trains leaving Hatfield and 14 leaving Herne Hill every day.<ref>{{cite journal |date=11 August 1866 |journal=The Railway News |page=136}}</ref> The LSWR began running trains between Ludgate Hill and [[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]] via Herne Hill when the Tulse Hill extension was completed.<ref name="Jackson_a" /> Some of these services went as far as [[Kingston railway station (London)|Kingston]] until the mid-1890s.<ref> [[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], fig. 53.</ref>

===Changes from 1870 to 1923===
By 1870, a track had been added to the east of the station and two sidings had been added to the west;<ref>{{cite book |last=Marshall |first=W.W. |title=Old Ordnance Survey Maps Brixton & Herne Hill 1870 |year=1988 |publisher=Alan Godfrey Maps |isbn=0-85054-151-4 |ref=harv }}</ref><ref>[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], map VIII.</ref> one of the western sidings was a [[bay platform]] for passenger trains, which was accessed from the platform adjoining the upper floor.<ref>[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], fig. 54.</ref> [[Interlocking]] signalling was in use at Herne Hill by 1880.<ref>[[#Kidner_1968|Kidner 1968]], p. 347.</ref>

The LCDR enlarged the station in 1884 to meet growing demand: the viaduct was widened to allow for the construction of a second island platform and two lines to the east<ref>{{cite journal |year=1884 |title=Miscellania |journal=The Builder |volume=47 |page=278 |publisher=The Builder, Covent Garden}}</ref> (the easternmost line was used only for freight<ref>[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], map IX.</ref>); and the foot tunnel under the viaduct was opened. In 1885, the LCDR decided to use [[Blackfriars Bridge railway station]] solely as a goods yard but lacked the space to sort wagons at the site.<ref name="Jackson_a" /><ref>[[#White_1971|White 1971]], p. 37.</ref> It purchased {{convert|14|acre|ha|1|lk=in|abbr=on}} of land between Herne Hill and Loughborough Junction for this purpose.<ref>[[#Kidner_1968|Kidner 1968]], p. 332.</ref> The Herne Hill Sorting Sidings had some 35 sidings, the longest of which was {{convert|940|ft|m|1|lk=in|abbr=on}}.<ref>[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], fig. 58.</ref> A stationmaster's house was built at 239 Railton Road in the mid-1880s as the site offered a good view of the station (it is now privately owned).<ref>[[#Herne_Hill_Society_2003|Herne Hill Society 2003]], p. 14.</ref> In 1888, Railton Road was extended to the Norwood Road/Half Moon Lane junction and Station Road ceased to exist.<ref name="HerneHill" />
[[File:Herne Hill railway OS Map 1894.jpg|thumb|left|alt=A black and white map of a railway station showing the position of tracks and platforms|An 1894 [[Ordnance Survey]] map showing the station's layout]]
At the beginning of 1899, the LCDR and the neighbouring [[South Eastern Railway, UK|South Eastern Railway]] (SER) handed over operation of their services to the newly-formed [[South Eastern and Chatham Railway]] (SECR), which was jointly owned by the two railways. The SECR ran the trains, but the lines and stations continued to be owned by the LCDR or SER.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Dendy Marshall |first1=C.F. |last2=Kidner |first2=R.W. |title=History of the Southern Railway |edition=2nd |year=1963 |origyear=1937 |publisher=[[Ian Allan]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=0-7110-0059-X |pages=314, 345, 355 |ref=harv }}</ref>

In 1900, it was suggested in ''[[The Contemporary Review]]'' that the City Branch should be replaced with an electric deep-level railway (i.e. a 'tube' line) between Herne Hill and Farringdon in order to remove Blackfriars Railway Bridge, which the author considered to be a blight on the Thames.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Strahan |first1=A. |year=1900 |journal=The Contemporary Review |volume=78 |page=109}}</ref>

A late-night service from Ludgate Hill (departing 01:15) to Beckenham Junction via Herne Hill began in 1910. The intention was to satisfy journalists on [[Fleet Street]] who regularly complained in print about the poor quality of service on the line; those working on the morning papers often worked beyond midnight and missed the last train.<ref>[[#Jackson_1969|Jackson 1969]], p. 199.</ref> 

Services to Farringdon from Herne Hill were discontinued in 1916 with the closure of Snow Hill tunnel to passengers, and trains from the south terminated at [[Holborn Viaduct railway station|Holborn Viaduct]] instead.<ref>[[#Jackson_1969|Jackson 1969]], p. 201.</ref><ref>[[#White_1971|White 1971]], p. 39.</ref> The LCDR amalgamated with the LB&SCR, SER and several other railways to form the [[Southern Railway (Great Britain)|Southern Railway]] at the start of 1923.<ref>{{cite book |last=Bonavia |first= Michael R. |title=History of the Southern Railway |year=1987 |publisher=Unwin Hyman |isbn= 978-0-04-385107-4 |page=26 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref>

===Modernisation===
Work began on electrifying the former LCDR suburban routes in 1924. Herne Hill station was extensively remodelled as part of these works: the eastern island platform was lengthened; the original island platform was demolished and replaced by one further west (allowing two tracks to be laid between the island platforms); the western sidings were removed; and the upper floor was closed to passengers.<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 27.</ref><ref>[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], fig. 65.</ref>

On 12 July 1925, a 660-volt [[Railway electrification in Great Britain#650 V - 750 V DC, third rail|third-rail system]] came into operation on both routes through Herne Hill: from Victoria to Orpington on the Chatham Main Line and along the entire length of the City Branch. Electric passenger services ran every 20&nbsp;minutes on both routes during the day<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 28.</ref> and electric trains were kept overnight at the sorting sidings, north of the station.<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 104.</ref>
[[File:Herne Hill Station Norwood 2012.jpg|thumb|alt=A railway bridge, painted green, over a road|The railway bridge over the junction of Norwood Road and Half Moon Lane]]
The distinctive signal box overlooking Norwood Road and a similar signal box at the northern end of the station were demolished in 1956 and replaced by a single signal box adjacent to the north junction.<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 154.</ref> The replacement signal box was in use from June 1956 until December 1981, when its functions were transferred to Victoria; the building still exists and is used by railway staff.<ref>[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], figs. 60,64.</ref> The signalling at Herne Hill was upgraded from [[Railway semaphore signal|semaphores]] to [[Railway signal#Colour light signals|colour lights]] on 8 March 1959 as part of the Kent Coast electrification plan.<ref>{{cite journal |date=11 August 1866 |journal=Railway gazette international |volume=110 |publisher=Reed Business |page=290}}</ref>

By 1959, the pattern of commuter services at Herne Hill had taken the shape it would hold into the 21st century: all-stop trains from Victoria to Orpington and from the City of London to Wimbledon and Sutton (but, unlike the modern Sutton Loop, via [[West Croydon station|West Croydon]]).<ref>[[#Jackson_1969|Jackson 1969]], p. 205.</ref> However, there was a decline in the number of electric passenger services on the Chatham Main Line through Herne Hill in the years after the war. Immediately after electrification in 1925, six trains used the route between Herne Hill and [[Shortlands railway station|Shortlands]] in each direction during every off-peak hour. By 1960, it had dropped to two trains in each direction.<ref>[[#White_1971|White 1971]], p. 64.</ref>

The Herne Hill Sorting Sidings closed on 1 August 1966 and the freight line to the east of the station was taken out of service.<ref name="MitchellSmith">[[#Mitchell_and_Smith_1992|Mitchell and Smith 1992]], fig. 61.</ref> Nothing of the sidings remains: residential accommodation has been built along Shakespeare Road (on the western sidings) and commercial premises have been built along Milkwood Road (on the eastern sidings).<ref>{{cite book |last=Herne Hill Society |title= A Glance at the History of Herne Hill |year=1992 |publisher= Herne Hill Society  |page=5 |location =London |ref=harv }}</ref>
[[File:Herne Hill Station 1862-2009 (Revised).gif|thumb|left|alt=An animation showing the changing layout. The station building is at the bottom. 1862: Station opens with one platform attached to building and one island platform above it, with two tracks between them. 1870: Sidings open to left of building and new track on far side of island platform. 1884: New island platform and two new tracks now at top. 1925: Sidings and building platform at bottom removed; top island platform is lengthened; island platform closest to building is moved closer to station, allowing two tracks between island platforms. 1966: Track at top, used for freight, is closed. 2009: Track at top is partially reopened as siding.|The changing layout. Crossovers and track curves omitted for clarity]]

===1988 to present===
In 1988, Snow Hill tunnel re-opened and the former LCDR City Branch formed the basis of the new [[Thameslink]] route. Network Rail began a major upgrade of the route in 2009. A key objective of the [[Thameslink Programme]] was allowing more trains to travel between central London and [[Brighton railway station|Brighton]], which was prevented by a bottleneck between London Bridge and Blackfriars on a viaduct through the historic [[Borough Market]]. Network Rail initially suggested widening the viaduct and demolishing part of the market, but the public backlash against this plan prompted Network Rail to consider permanently routing all Thameslink trains to/from Brighton via Herne Hill, avoiding London Bridge and the market.<ref name="Thameslink">[[#Thameslink2000_2004|Thameslink 2000 (2004)]], p. 8.</ref> This would have required the grade separation of the two lines through Herne Hill, which would have been achieved by constructing a new viaduct immediately to the east of the existing viaduct and using a [[Overpass|fly-over]] to connect the southern end of the new viaduct to the line between Tulse Hill and North Dulwich (taking the tracks over the Chatham Main Line and towards Tulse Hill).<ref>[[#Thameslink2000_2004|Thameslink 2000 (2004)]], p. 10.</ref> This proposal was rejected in 2004 because of its environmental impact on Herne Hill and the larger number of interchanges offered on the London Bridge route; the Borough Market viaduct was widened instead.<ref name="Thameslink" /> From December 2008 to May 2012, Thameslink services serving Herne Hill did not run most weekends or after 22:30 every week-night because of construction work on the Thameslink route through central London as part of the Thameslink Programme.<ref>[http://thameslinkprogramme.co.uk/faqs/faqs_categories/public_index#question_48 Question 48], Thameslink Programme. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref>

During the initial planning in the late 1980s for [[High Speed 1]] (HS1; a high-speed railway line between London and the [[Channel Tunnel]]), [[British Rail]] considered building the line to serve a low-level station at [[London King's Cross railway station|King's Cross]] via south London.<ref>{{cite news |url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/7082392.stm | title = How St Pancras was chosen | work = BBC News Online | location=London | date=14 November 2007 | accessdate = 19 November 2007 | first=Trevor | last=Timpson}}</ref> An option for this route was via Herne Hill, which would have required quadrupling the tracks on the Chatham Main Line between Shortlands and Herne Hill and on the City Branch to Loughborough Junction;<ref>{{cite news | title = British Rail sets out timetable for train services to the Channel tunnel | work = The Times | location=London | date=15 July 1988 | first=Cowton | last=Rodney}}</ref> it was estimated that this would have led to the loss of 90<U+2013>180 homes in Lambeth.<ref>{{cite news | title = Thousand of homes at risk in choice of Channel tunnel link | work = The Times | location=London | date=5 December 1988 | first=Cowton | last=Rodney}}</ref> Although both a different route and London terminus for HS1 were eventually chosen (St Pancras via East London), [[Eurostar]] services linking [[London Waterloo station|London Waterloo]] to Brussels and Paris passed through Herne Hill without stopping<ref>{{cite book  |title=Channel Tunnel International Rail Link |publisher= British Rail |at=Passenger train routes - Infrastructure and train movements |url= http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/BRB_ChannelTunnel003.pdf |accessdate=4 May 2012}}</ref> from 1994 until the completion of HS1 in November 2007. This marked the end of rail services to the continent via Herne Hill, which had been started by the LCDR in 1863 when the line between Victoria and Dover via Herne Hill was completed.
[[File:Herne Hill railway station - Upper floor entrances.jpg|thumb|alt=A brick building on the far side of a railway track, behind a blue metal fence. All of the doors and windows have been bricked up.|The sealed entrances and windows of the station's upper floor]]
The upper floor of the station, which had not been used by passengers since 1925, was converted into {{convert|3000|sqft|sqm|1|lk=in|abbr=on}} of office space in 1991 and rented as 'Tower House' (after the station's distinctive tower).<ref name="MitchellSmith" /> The disused freight line to the east of the station was partly reopened in 2009 as a siding for use by First Capital Connect trains to compensate for the loss of sidings when the [[Moorgate station|Moorgate]] Thameslink branch was closed.<ref>{{cite book |title= Variation to Proposed G1 Network Change: Herne Hill Turnback Facilities |year=2008|publisher= Network Rail |url=http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/network%20code/network%20change/completed%20proposals/thameslink/ng2008tlpoo1herne%20hill/ncg12008tlp001v2%20herne%20hill.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref><ref name="southernelectric" /> The line's connection to the south junction was severed during these works. The station had become fully accessible by 2010: lifts were installed to provide step-free access to the platforms in 2008<ref>{{cite book |title= Herne Hill Society Newsletter |year=2008|publisher= Herne Hill Society |page=5 |url=http://www.hernehillsociety.org.uk/hhs_pdfs/HerneHillNews104.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> and a unisex disabled-accessible toilet was opened on the southbound platforms in 2010.<ref>[http://www.southeasternrailway.co.uk/download/6415.5/disabled-persons-protection-policy-guide-2011/ Disabled Peoples Protection Policy, p. 5.] London & Southeastern Railway. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref>

===Accidents and disruption===
Railway services through Herne Hill were affected by [[World War II]]. Passenger services on the City Branch were reduced from September 1939 to once every 30&nbsp;minutes during the week and hourly at weekends;<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 107.</ref> and the line was cut twice during [[the Blitz]]. On the second occasion, the railway bridge over Hinton Road (immediately south of Loughborough Junction) was destroyed.<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 114.</ref> The route between Holborn Viaduct and Herne Hill was disrupted by 62 incidents during the war.<ref>[[#Moody_1957|Moody 1957]], p. 115.</ref>

[[File:Herne Hill Sorting Sidings.jpg|thumb|alt=A pencil-drawn diagram showing approximately 30 sidings, evenly split between the top and bottom of the diagram; a railway line runs through the middle of the diagram.|A map showing the layout of the former sidings north of Herne Hill and the point of the 1960 collision]]
On 6 November 1947, a steam train approaching from West Dulwich passed a [[Signal passed at danger|signal at danger]] in heavy fog and crashed into an electric train crossing the station's south junction towards Tulse Hill. One passenger onboard the electric train was killed and nine others were hospitalised.<ref>{{cite book |last=Wilson |first=G.R.S. |title= Railway Accidents: Report on the Collision which occurred on 6th November, 1947, at Herne Hill on the Southern Railway |year=1948 |publisher=Ministry of Transport |location=London |url=http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_HerneHill1947.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> 

A minor accident occurred on 30 June 1957. A light engine, travelling towards Tulse Hill, was waiting to cross the south junction when it was struck from behind by an express passenger service from Victoria that had passed a signal at danger. The driver of the light engine and two passengers from the express train were hospitalised but quickly discharged.<ref>{{cite book |last=McMullen |first=D. |title=Railway Accidents: Report on the collision which occurred on 30th June 1957 at Herne Hill in the Southern Region British Railways |year=1957 |publisher=Ministry of Transport and Civil Aviation |location= London |url= http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_HerneHill1957.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> 

A second fatal collision occurred at the sorting sidings, just north of the station, on 1 April 1960 in fog that reduced visibility to {{convert|60|ft|m|1|lk=in|abbr=on}}. A steam locomotive was waiting on the southbound track outside Herne Hill for a proceed signal when the signalman cleared an electric passenger service (behind the steam locomotive) to proceed down the same track. The steam locomotive was struck from behind, destroying it and killing the electric train's driver.<ref>{{cite book |last= Reed |first=W.P. |title=Railway Accidents: Report on the collision which occurred on 1st April 1960 at Herne Hill Sorting Sidings signal box in the Southern Region British Railways |year=1957 |publisher=Ministry of Transport, His Majesty's Stationery Office |location=London |url= http://www.railwaysarchive.co.uk/documents/MoT_HerneHill1957.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>

On 8 May 2004, there was a security alert at the station after a train driver reported seeing a man in camouflage gear with a rocket launcher on a platform. In fact, the man was a local [[Street performance|busker]] carrying a [[didgeridoo]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Rail disruption blamed on didgeridoo | work = This is Local London | location=London | date=20 May 2004 }}</ref>

==Future==
===Services===
The route through the station will be busier from 2015 as Thameslink trains serving [[London Bridge station|London Bridge]] will be diverted via Herne Hill<ref>[http://thameslinkprogramme.co.uk/cms/pages/view/64 A new station for London Bridge], Thameslink Programme. Retrieved 20 April 2012.</ref> - an additional four trains per hour in both directions.<ref name="NetworkRail">[[#NetworkRail_March2008|Network Rail March 2008]], p. 92.</ref> This is due to the [[London Bridge station#Future_development|redevelopment of London Bridge]] that will temporarily close it to [[Thameslink#Route|Bedford-Brighton]] trains. The additional trains will not call at Herne Hill; instead, they will run fast between [[Blackfriars station|London Blackfriars]] and [[East Croydon station|East Croydon]].<ref name="NetworkRail" /> It would not be possible for the 12-car peak services to call at Herne Hill in any event as the station's platforms are too short and it would not be viable to use [[selective door operation]] as the carriages not on the platforms would foul the junctions.<ref name="NetworkRail_a">[[#NetworkRail_March2008|Network Rail March 2008]], p. 128.</ref>
[[File:Herne Hill Station Layout 2012 (Revised).png|thumb|alt=A diagram showing the tracks, platforms and cross-overs at Herne Hill station in 2012. From the bottom to top (west to east): the station building; a railway track; an island platform; two railway tracks; a second island platform; a railway track; and a siding. There are two junctions at each end of the station.|Contemporary layout of tracks and structures at Herne Hill station]]

[[Network Rail]], in its July 2011 London & South East [[route utilisation strategy]], has recommended that all services from Herne Hill towards Blackfriars should terminate in the [[Bay platform|bay platforms]] at Blackfriars after London Bridge's redevelopment is completed in 2018<ref>[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], p. 71.</ref> and the diverted Thameslink trains return there.<ref>[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], p. 20.</ref> Passengers from Herne Hill would then have to change at Blackfriars to travel further north. Network Rail has made this recommendation because more services will be using the route between [[St Pancras railway station|St. Pancras]] and London Bridge from 2018;<ref name="NetworkRail_b" /> sending trains from Herne Hill to the terminating platforms on the western side of Blackfriars (instead of the through tracks on the eastern side of the station) will remove the need for them to cross in front of trains to/from [[Denmark Hill]] and trains to/from London Bridge at junctions south of Blackfriars.<ref>[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], p.80.</ref>

It is anticipated there will be six trains to Blackfriars from Herne Hill during peak hours from 2018 (four from Sutton and two from Kent House) and four trains from Sutton during off-peak hours.<ref name="NetworkRail_b">[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], p. 72.</ref> There will also be two trains between [[Medway|Medway, Kent]] and Blackfriars via Herne Hill during peak hours, but they will not call at the station.<ref>[http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/kent/kent%20rus.pdf Assumed Kent main line services following completion of construction works at London Bridge, p. 187.], Network Rail. Retrieved 20 April 2012.</ref>

The [[Department for Transport]] has yet to decide whether the Sutton Loop will remain part of the Thameslink service after 2018 and receive the [[Thameslink rolling stock programme|new Thameslink trains]].<ref>[http://thameslinkprogramme.co.uk/faqs/faqs_categories/public_index#question_41 Question 41], Thameslink Programme. Retrieved 20 April 2012.</ref> In the longer term, Network Rail has forecast that by 2031 there will be 900 more passengers attempting to travel on the route between Herne Hill and Blackfriars during the busiest peak hour every weekday than can be accommodated on the trains.<ref>[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], p. 102.</ref> It is anticipated that eight-car trains with higher capacity (similar to the [[British Rail Class 378|Class 378]] trains used on inner London metro routes) will eventually be required to address this shortfall.<ref name="NetworkRail_c">[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], p. 139.</ref>

===Station infrastructure===
[[File:Herne Hill Station South Junction 2012.jpg|thumb|The current southern [[Level junction|flat junction]] at Herne Hill, considered for [[grade separation]]|alt=A pair of third-rail railway tracks are intersected by a second pair of tracks coming in from the right]]
The route from Victoria to Orpington via Herne Hill is projected to be amongst the most congested and overcrowded in South East London by 2026.<ref>[http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm200910/cmselect/cmtran/38/38we52.htm Stress on the London Rail Network, Figure 2], Transport Committee. Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref> Network Rail is considering [[Grade separation|grade-separating]] the two lines passing through Herne Hill so that trains would not cross each other's paths at the station's junctions;<ref name="NetworkRail_d">[[#NetworkRail_March2008|Network Rail March 2008]], p. 145.</ref> this restricts the number of services that can pass through the station. A 2008 route utilisation strategy for South London concluded that this improvement will not be required before 2020 but recommended safeguarding the required land.<ref name="NetworkRail_d" /> Grade-separation is supported by Southeastern<ref>{{cite book |chapter= Options considered to bridge the gap between present demand and future growth |title= Response to Route Utilisation Strategy consultation |year= 2007 |publisher= Southeastern |page=3 |url= http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/south%20london/consultation%20responses/s/southeastern.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> and First Capital Connect believes it should be given more consideration,<ref>{{cite book |title= Consultation Response <U+2013> South London route utilisation strategy |year=2007 |publisher= First Capital Connect |page=1 |url= http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/south%20london/consultation%20responses/f/first%20capital%20connect.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> but Network Rail has stated that it would be difficult to carry out the work because the station is on a viaduct and surrounded by buildings.<ref>{{cite book |chapter= Rail Overcrowding |title= Transport Committee 13 November 2008 |year=2008 |publisher= [[London Assembly]] |page=28 |url= http://legacy.london.gov.uk/assembly/transport/2008/nov13/minutes/appendix-a.rtf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> The 2011 route utilisation strategy, which examined options for congestion relief at Herne Hill before 2031, did not suggest grade-separation as an option in the 2011<U+2013>2031 period.<ref name="NetworkRail_b" /><ref name="NetworkRail_c" />

This project would also enable the platforms at Herne Hill to be lengthened to accommodate 12-car trains as the current northern junction, which prevents them from being extended, would be removed.<ref name="NetworkRail_a" /> However, longer trains could not be used on the Sutton Loop without also rebuilding Tulse Hill and Elephant & Castle.<ref>[[#NetworkRail_July2011|Network Rail July 2011]], pp. 138<U+2013>139.</ref>

The congestion within the station itself has been noted by Network Rail and it is keeping the situation under review.<ref>{{cite book |chapter= Gaps and Options |title= Network RUS Stations |year=2011 |publisher= Network Rail |page=57 |url= http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/network/working%20group%202%20-%20stations/networkrusstations.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> [[Transport for London]] (TfL) has recommended that specific improvement works (new entrance doors, removal of interior wall, wider stairs to platforms and second station entrance) be carried out between 2014 and 2019.<ref>{{cite book |chapter= Summary of recommendations at Strategic Interchanges |title= Delivering the Mayor's Transport Strategy: National Rail in London |year=2011 |publisher=Transport for London |page=71 |url= http://www.tfl.gov.uk/assets/downloads/businessandpartners/delivering-the-mayors-transport-strategy-tfls-hlos2-recommendations-final.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref>

TfL has also suggested there may be potential for the turnaround siding adjacent to Milkwood Road to be converted for passenger use.<ref>{{cite book |chapter=9.4 Gap H: Elephant & Castle corridor |title= London and South East RUS Consultation Response |year=2011 |publisher=Transport for London |url= http://www.networkrail.co.uk/browse%20documents/rus%20documents/route%20utilisation%20strategies/rus%20generation%202/london%20and%20south%20east/consultation%20responses/t/transport%20for%20london.pdf |accessdate=20 April 2012}}</ref> This would require substantial changes to the station as there is no direct access to the platforms from Milkwood Road and the current corridor for accessing the platforms does not extend any further east than the southbound platform.<ref name="nationalrail" />

===Incorporation into London Overground===
The [[Mayor of London]] published a long-term vision for the [[London Overground]] in February 2012.<ref>[[#GLA_Feb2012|Greater London Authority, February 2012]]</ref> It recommends that all London suburban rail services should eventually be devolved to TfL and that suburban services currently provided by Southeastern be devolved by 2020 to demonstrate the benefits of this approach.<ref>[[#GLA_Feb2012|Greater London Authority, February 2012]], p. 23.</ref> Southeastern's suburban services include the route between Victoria and Orpington via Herne Hill.<ref>[[#SE_May2012|Southeastern 2012]], p. 30.</ref>

===Victoria line extension===
TfL has considered extending the [[Victoria line]] to Herne Hill to provide faster turnaround at the southern end of the line. The extension is not a priority for TfL as it has a weaker business case than other infrastructure projects.<ref>[http://www.london.gov.uk/mqt/public/question.do?id=10620 Transport Plan <U+2013> Southward Extensions], [[London Assembly]] Retrieved 20 April 2012</ref>

==Service pattern==
[[File:Herne Hill - Side.jpg|thumb|alt=A brick building with decorative brickwork; a tower can be seen to the left and a stairway to the right. The main entrance is at the centre of the building; a taxi office is to the entrance's right.|The station as seen from the southern end of Railton Road]]
The station is managed by [[Southeastern (train operating company)|Southeastern]] [[train operating company]]. The off-peak service pattern {{As of|2012|05|df=y|lc=on}} is:

* Two trains per hour (tph) to {{Stnlnk|Luton}} via {{Stnlnk|Elephant & Castle}}<ref name="FirstCapital">[[#FCC_May2012|First Capital Connect 2012]], p. 115.</ref> 
* 2&nbsp;tph to {{Stnlnk|St Albans}} via Elephant & Castle<ref name="FirstCapital" />
* 4&nbsp;tph to [[London Victoria station|London Victoria]] via {{Stnlnk|Brixton}}<ref>[[#SE_May2012|Southeastern 2012]], p. 52.</ref>  
* 4&nbsp;tph to {{Stnlnk|Orpington}} via [[Beckenham Junction station|Beckenham Junction]]<ref>[[#SE_May2012|Southeastern 2012]], p. 34.</ref> 
* 2&nbsp;tph to [[Sutton railway station (London)|Sutton]] via [[Wimbledon station|Wimbledon]]<ref name="FirstCapital_a">[[#FCC_May2012|First Capital Connect 2012]], p. 107.</ref>
* 2&nbsp;tph to Sutton via {{Stnlnk|Mitcham Eastfields}}<ref name="FirstCapital_a" />

On Sunday, northbound Sutton Loop trains alternate between terminating at Blackfriars and Luton.<ref>[[#FCC_May2012|First Capital Connect 2012]], p. 120.</ref> Late-night Sutton Loop services (21:57 onwards) run to {{Stnlnk|Bedford}} from Monday-Saturday and terminate at Blackfriars on Sunday.<ref>[[#FCC_May2012|First Capital Connect 2012]], p. 116.</ref>

First Capital Connect and Southeastern jointly operate additional [[Rush hour#United_Kingdom|peak]] services from Herne Hill to Beford (morning and evening peaks),<ref>[[#FCC_May2012|First Capital Connect 2012]], pp. 126,115.</ref> Beckenham Junction, {{Stnlnk|Kent House}}, {{Stnlnk|Rochester}} and {{Stnlnk|Swanley}} (evening peak only).<ref>[[#FCC_May2012|First Capital Connect 2012]], pp. 107,123.</ref>

